1
00:00:02,880 --> 00:00:04,871
<i>He's a Chief inspector.</i>

2
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:06,400
I reckon it's communists he's after.

3
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:08,677
So this copper's going
to leave us alone, right?

4
00:00:08,920 --> 00:00:11,639
-What the fuck!
-[GROANING]

5
00:00:12,480 --> 00:00:15,472
I want you to see this as me
introducing myself to you.

6
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:18,789
He said Mr. Churchill sent him
to Birmingham.

7
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:20,632
Something about a robbery.

8
00:00:21,440 --> 00:00:24,034
Thomas, you're a bookmaker.
You're not a fool.

9
00:00:24,480 --> 00:00:27,199
You sell these guns to anyone who has
use to them, you will hang.

10
00:00:27,880 --> 00:00:30,520
I'm just a poor communist frog
with a big mouth.

11
00:00:30,680 --> 00:00:33,593
I'm with you 'cause you're the
only man around here not scared of them.

12
00:00:34,320 --> 00:00:36,311
The only difference between
you and me, Freddie,

13
00:00:36,400 --> 00:00:39,791
is that, sometimes, my horses
stand a chance of winning.

14
00:00:40,200 --> 00:00:41,200
Tommy!

15
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:43,714
You're fixing races now.

16
00:00:44,840 --> 00:00:46,520
GRACE:
<i>I'm here about the job as a barmaid.</i>

17
00:00:49,320 --> 00:00:50,320
Are you in position?

18
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:52,640
I am, sir.

19
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:33,154
<i>♪ Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track</i>

20
00:01:35,640 --> 00:01:39,713
<i>♪ Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

21
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:43,759
<i>♪ As it shifts and cracks</i>

22
00:01:43,840 --> 00:01:49,631
<i>♪ Where secrets lie in the border fires
in the humming wires... ♪</i>

23
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:51,996
I thought you said we were
going to the fair.

24
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:57,435
We have business first.
Come on. Bring your wits.

25
00:01:57,800 --> 00:01:59,677
-What business?
-That's the Lee family.

26
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:02,871
-Tommy!
-Johnny-dogs!

27
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:05,153
Tommy, how the hell are ya?

28
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,754
All the better for getting
the city smoke out of me lungs.

29
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,116
I thought you became
a bit too grand for us.

30
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:13,397
-I've been busy.
-I'm riding with the Lee family now.

31
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:17,151
I heard. Myself, I'd rather
live among pigs.

32
00:02:17,560 --> 00:02:19,312
Come on, Tommy, no disputing.

33
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:21,480
So your first fair since France?

34
00:02:22,520 --> 00:02:25,876
What do you know about France?
You war-shy, gypsy bastard.

35
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:30,040
-So this is the horse?
-And that's the car.

36
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:46,235
Hang on a minute.

37
00:02:47,280 --> 00:02:50,477
You're not swapping the family car
for a bloody horse.

38
00:02:50,680 --> 00:02:52,398
Of course we're not swapping it.

39
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:54,438
Huh? That'd be mad.

40
00:02:54,520 --> 00:02:55,874
We're gonna play two up.

41
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:18,311
-TOMMY: Here you are.
-Yeah, I knew it.

42
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:21,234
See, I knew it. Tommy, you bloody idiot.

43
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:22,594
Shut up, Arthur, I won.

44
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:23,995
Oi!

45
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:26,600
I promised Johnny I'd let him have
a spin in the car if he lost.

46
00:03:27,120 --> 00:03:28,997
-[MEN LAUGHING]
-All right.

47
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:35,478
Are you Lee boys laughing at my brother?

48
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:39,320
Are ya?

49
00:03:40,440 --> 00:03:42,636
-Eh?
-Tommy! Tommy, come on!

50
00:03:42,720 --> 00:03:45,633
-I asked you a question.
-Tommy, come on, it's just the craic.

51
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:47,675
Get your family out of here,

52
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:51,071
and go and enjoy yourselves at the fair
before they start a war. Huh?

53
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:53,754
[SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

54
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:01,236
Yeah, but his mum was a didicoy whore.

55
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:05,078
[BELL TOLLING]

56
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:31,638
We will take them
before last night's beer

57
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:33,872
turns to piss and wakes the devils up.

58
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:37,191
We will leave no stone unturned.

59
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:40,750
Every gun, every bullet
will be brought to me for inspection.

60
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:44,793
Now, take your positions.

61
00:06:06,640 --> 00:06:07,640
[ALL SHOUTING]

62
00:06:08,720 --> 00:06:09,720
[GROANING]

63
00:06:12,560 --> 00:06:16,679
[WOMAN SHOUTING]

64
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:19,313
[BOTH MOANING]

65
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:24,833
Freddie... [MOANING]

66
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:25,920
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

67
00:06:26,480 --> 00:06:28,153
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

68
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:30,616
Are you sure your brothers
are at the fair?

69
00:06:30,640 --> 00:06:32,080
If it was them, they wouldn't knock.

70
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:33,560
MAN: Mr. Thorne!

71
00:06:34,880 --> 00:06:35,950
What is it?

72
00:06:36,040 --> 00:06:37,880
MAN: The police are rounding up
the communists.

73
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:42,512
Come on, Ada. If the cops find me,
we're screwed. Fuck!

74
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:47,070
Ada.

75
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:07,836
You have to jump, Ada. I'll catch ya.

76
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,000
Come on.

77
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:11,920
[YELPS]

78
00:07:17,200 --> 00:07:18,200
Look at this.

79
00:07:19,040 --> 00:07:22,954
A prescription for iron tablets
for Ada fucking Shelby.

80
00:07:24,560 --> 00:07:25,595
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

81
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:28,874
Mrs. Donovan, I need that favor.

82
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:30,920
-Come in and be quick.
-I'm not coming in. She is.

83
00:07:31,120 --> 00:07:32,952
Holy Jesus! It's the Shelby girl.

84
00:07:33,120 --> 00:07:34,696
You've not seen her with me,
okay, Mrs. Donovan?

85
00:07:34,720 --> 00:07:35,856
Just give her a cup of tea
and let her stay

86
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:36,920
until the police are gone.

87
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:39,713
She's the sister of those
Peaky Blinder devils.

88
00:07:39,800 --> 00:07:42,713
And, yet, she's an angel. Come on, Ada.

89
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:45,154
What are you gonna do, Freddie?

90
00:07:45,240 --> 00:07:47,117
Me? I'm gonna have to leave town
for a bit.

91
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:53,558
[IN DISTINCT SHOUTING]

92
00:07:57,960 --> 00:07:59,951
[DOOR OPENING]

93
00:08:00,120 --> 00:08:01,554
[DOOR CLOSING]

94
00:08:05,320 --> 00:08:07,311
A gentleman would take off his hat.

95
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:10,389
Put out his pipe.

96
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:21,073
I see you Specials only dare come here

97
00:08:21,160 --> 00:08:23,037
when you know
the boys are away at the fair.

98
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:25,275
You mean your nephews?

99
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:30,360
With their guns and their razors?
Is it them you're lighting candles for?

100
00:08:31,840 --> 00:08:32,910
No.

101
00:08:33,800 --> 00:08:35,800
I'm lighting candles for the boys
from The Garrison

102
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:37,757
who lost their lives in France.

103
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:41,152
There's a list there.

104
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:43,875
Look.

105
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:51,629
I hear you didn't make it to France,

106
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:52,790
Inspector Campbell.

107
00:08:56,240 --> 00:08:57,958
You've heard of me?

108
00:08:59,520 --> 00:09:00,715
I've heard of you.

109
00:09:04,560 --> 00:09:06,160
Is it the Holy Grail you're looking for?

110
00:09:07,080 --> 00:09:08,479
As a matter of fact,

111
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,389
it is the Holy Grail I'm looking for.

112
00:09:11,920 --> 00:09:16,949
Something precious, something stolen.
Perhaps you know what I'm talking about.

113
00:09:20,360 --> 00:09:23,910
Sorry. I misunderstood your intention
when you pushed me against the wall.

114
00:09:37,200 --> 00:09:39,635
Turn the place upside down.

115
00:09:42,760 --> 00:09:44,876
Arthur Shelby said you people
would help us.

116
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:47,576
If we don't know what you've lost,
how can we help you find it?

117
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:50,433
But I have found out subsequently
that I was speaking to the wrong man.

118
00:09:50,760 --> 00:09:53,559
Next time, I want to talk to the boss.

119
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,550
Lickey Tea Rooms. Friday, 10:00.

120
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:01,350
And when I say "the boss,"
I mean Thomas.

121
00:10:07,240 --> 00:10:08,355
Come on.

122
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:36,437
Now what the bloody hell's
been going on here?

123
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:40,435
Jesus Christ.

124
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,800
The coppers told everyone Arthur
had agreed to it when he was arrested.

125
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:47,312
They said the Peaky Blinders had cleared
out to the fair to let them do it.

126
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:50,198
No one never said nothing to that copper

127
00:10:50,280 --> 00:10:52,351
about smashing up bloody houses!

128
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:54,556
All right. Which pubs did they do?

129
00:10:54,920 --> 00:10:56,911
The Guns, The Chain, The Marquis.

130
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:58,911
All the ones that pay you
to protect them.

131
00:10:59,280 --> 00:11:01,430
The only one they didn't touch
was The Garrison.

132
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,752
Made sure people think we were in on it.

133
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:07,320
Smart, this copper.

134
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:11,953
So go on. Drink your beers. Get out.

135
00:11:12,240 --> 00:11:14,709
You better show people
you'll still the cocks of the walk.

136
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:17,189
Hand out some cash
to the landlords of the pubs.

137
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:19,078
Pay some veterans to fix the places up.

138
00:11:19,480 --> 00:11:21,039
Give us the bag.

139
00:11:21,360 --> 00:11:22,998
So what about you, Tommy?

140
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:26,073
I've to go to Charlie's
to stable the horse.

141
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:27,953
Looked foot sore in the box.

142
00:11:31,920 --> 00:11:33,319
Let them see your faces.

143
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:43,920
So we both know what
they were looking for.

144
00:11:50,400 --> 00:11:51,549
You don't read the papers?

145
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:53,315
Racing papers.

146
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:55,400
So let me tell you the odds.

147
00:11:56,520 --> 00:11:58,670
I reckon it's 3-to-1
there'll be a revolution.

148
00:11:59,440 --> 00:12:00,589
I wouldn't bet on that.

149
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:02,360
That copper's betting on it.

150
00:12:03,520 --> 00:12:05,720
He's not gonna let it rest
till he gets those guns back.

151
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:13,515
[SIGHS]

152
00:12:14,240 --> 00:12:15,594
Did he talk to ya, Pol?

153
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:18,595
In the church.

154
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:21,195
Did he try to find our Ada?

155
00:12:22,960 --> 00:12:24,109
She was sleeping.

156
00:12:24,880 --> 00:12:25,950
[SCOFFS]

157
00:12:27,800 --> 00:12:29,074
Where was she sleeping, Pol?

158
00:12:31,360 --> 00:12:33,351
I thought you didn't care
for women's business.

159
00:12:40,040 --> 00:12:41,439
He knows you're the boss.

160
00:12:42,040 --> 00:12:43,360
He wants to meet you.

161
00:12:49,880 --> 00:12:51,712
-Will you talk to him?
-No.

162
00:12:53,840 --> 00:12:55,640
You don't parlay when you're
on the back foot.

163
00:12:58,480 --> 00:13:00,391
We'll strike a blow back first.

164
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:17,750
BARMAN: Hey, lad.

165
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:20,470
-What are you doing?
-We're having a fire.

166
00:13:20,680 --> 00:13:21,875
[RAPID KNOCKING AT DOOR]

167
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:23,993
Take off your picture of the King.

168
00:13:24,080 --> 00:13:25,080
What?

169
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:26,800
-Bring it to Watery Lane.
-[COIN CLANGING]

170
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:30,433
[MEN TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

171
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:32,040
[LAUGHING]

172
00:13:39,360 --> 00:13:40,475
[ALL CHEERING]

173
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:49,955
Chuck them on, boys.

174
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:51,560
-[ALL CHEERING]
-ALL: Yeah!

175
00:13:55,600 --> 00:13:57,637
Well, I hope to God you
know what you're doing.

176
00:13:59,640 --> 00:14:00,710
[ALL CHEERING]

177
00:14:18,320 --> 00:14:19,435
I'm the reporter.

178
00:14:19,720 --> 00:14:21,279
The <i>Birmingham Evening Despatch.</i>

179
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:23,150
I had a phone call.

180
00:14:24,200 --> 00:14:25,952
Someone called Thomas Shelby?

181
00:14:26,760 --> 00:14:28,034
Come with me.

182
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:32,999
Move aside. Give us a bit of room.
Tommy.

183
00:14:34,440 --> 00:14:36,078
Move back for us, please, folks.

184
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:37,275
You're Mr. Shelby?

185
00:14:37,360 --> 00:14:38,840
-MAN: All the way back, please.
-I am.

186
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:43,559
You said I would be protected.

187
00:14:44,120 --> 00:14:45,554
You're protected.

188
00:14:46,640 --> 00:14:47,960
What's going on?

189
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:50,557
There are some things I want you
to write down.

190
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:53,829
Now, first of all.

191
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:56,994
It's not the people around here
that are disloyal to the King.

192
00:14:57,560 --> 00:14:59,073
It's the opposite.

193
00:14:59,720 --> 00:15:01,358
You see, we don't want our beloved king

194
00:15:01,440 --> 00:15:03,875
looking down and seeing the things
that have been done to us.

195
00:15:04,720 --> 00:15:06,552
So we are taking down his pictures.

196
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:08,074
But why are you burning them?

197
00:15:09,120 --> 00:15:11,873
We went through hell for our king.

198
00:15:12,320 --> 00:15:15,039
Walked through the flames of war.
Write all this down!

199
00:15:15,480 --> 00:15:17,710
And now we're being attacked
in our own homes.

200
00:15:18,880 --> 00:15:21,076
These new coppers over from Belfast,

201
00:15:21,240 --> 00:15:23,709
breaking into our homes
and interfering with our women.

202
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:26,309
We don't think our king
would want to see that happening.

203
00:15:27,720 --> 00:15:29,757
So we are lighting fires
to raise the alarm.

204
00:15:30,840 --> 00:15:33,673
May I ask you,
in what capacity do you speak?

205
00:15:34,280 --> 00:15:35,350
No capacity.

206
00:15:36,320 --> 00:15:37,355
I'm an ordinary man.

207
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:39,952
I won gallantry medals at the Somme.

208
00:15:41,360 --> 00:15:43,636
I want you to write in your paper
what's going on here.

209
00:15:45,800 --> 00:15:46,915
Go on, go.

210
00:15:55,680 --> 00:15:56,750
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

211
00:15:56,840 --> 00:15:57,910
Come in.

212
00:15:58,000 --> 00:15:59,070
[DOOR OPENING]

213
00:16:00,920 --> 00:16:02,479
MAN: There... There...

214
00:16:03,040 --> 00:16:06,192
There's a telephone call for you, sir,
on the London line.

215
00:16:06,280 --> 00:16:08,396
There is? It's almost midnight.

216
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:11,278
It's Mr. Winston Churchill, sir.

217
00:16:24,480 --> 00:16:26,551
-Yes, sir.
-Inspector Campbell.

218
00:16:26,920 --> 00:16:29,355
I hear there's been a bonfire
in your city.

219
00:16:29,880 --> 00:16:33,350
There was a small fire reported
around 9:00 in Watery Lane.

220
00:16:33,800 --> 00:16:35,520
<i>Certainly nothing to trouble
you about, sir.</i>

221
00:16:35,760 --> 00:16:38,070
Ah, but I'm afraid it has troubled me.

222
00:16:38,760 --> 00:16:42,116
Half an hour ago,
I received a wire communication

223
00:16:42,200 --> 00:16:45,079
from the editor of the
<i>Birmingham Evening Despatch.</i>

224
00:16:46,160 --> 00:16:49,551
<i>It seems one of his reporters
was invited to the fire</i>

225
00:16:49,640 --> 00:16:52,996
<i>and discovered that they were burning
pictures of the King.</i>

226
00:16:53,640 --> 00:16:54,675
Of the King?

227
00:16:55,400 --> 00:16:58,552
Any newspaper report
which may cause embarrassment

228
00:16:58,640 --> 00:17:01,200
to His Majesty is always referred first,

229
00:17:01,280 --> 00:17:03,954
and as a matter of routine,
to the Home Office.

230
00:17:04,320 --> 00:17:06,880
I will go down there immediately,
and, er, arrest those involved.

231
00:17:07,600 --> 00:17:10,831
No, you most certainly will not
make arrests.

232
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:13,590
<i>If there are arrests,
there will be trials.</i>

233
00:17:13,680 --> 00:17:17,230
If there are trials, there will be
more newspaper reports

234
00:17:17,320 --> 00:17:21,518
which will necessarily mention
the burning of the King's likeness.

235
00:17:22,040 --> 00:17:26,318
I put you in Birmingham
for one very specific reason.

236
00:17:26,760 --> 00:17:30,390
Are you any nearer to finding
those stolen guns?

237
00:17:30,600 --> 00:17:32,750
-We are making steady progress.
-We need results.

238
00:17:32,840 --> 00:17:34,956
Goodnight, Mr. Campbell.

239
00:17:35,040 --> 00:17:37,350
<i>Sir...</i> [CLEARS THROAT]
<i>Could I at least ask...</i>

240
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:40,512
Does this report
name any of those involved?

241
00:17:41,520 --> 00:17:43,511
It names a Mr. Thomas Shelby.

242
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,150
The report mentions he's a war hero.

243
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:47,750
[PHONE LINE CUTS OUT]

244
00:17:57,440 --> 00:17:58,635
Good of you to join us.

245
00:17:59,800 --> 00:18:01,632
-Where have you been all day?
-ADA: In bed.

246
00:18:02,960 --> 00:18:06,112
Couldn't sleep. Then I couldn't wake up.

247
00:18:06,680 --> 00:18:09,274
Then I was cold, and then
I had to go for a wee.

248
00:18:10,160 --> 00:18:12,879
Then I was with this bear on a boat.

249
00:18:12,960 --> 00:18:16,590
That was just a dream.
Then I was hungry.

250
00:18:17,360 --> 00:18:18,634
Why are you reading the paper?

251
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:21,390
